context: The szlachta ([ˈʂlaxta] ( listen), exonym: Nobility) was a legally privileged <a0_0>noble class<a0_0/> with origins in the Kingdom of Poland. It gained considerable institutional privileges between 1333 and 1370 during the reign of <a1_0>King Casimir III the Great<a1_0/>.:211 In 1413, following a series of tentative personal unions between the <a2_0>Grand Duchy of Lithuania and the Crown Kingdom of Poland<a2_0/>, the existing Lithuanian nobility formally joined this class.:211 As the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth (<a3_0>1569–1795<a3_0/>) evolved and expanded in territory, its membership grew to include the leaders of <a4_0>Ducal Prussia<a4_0/>, Podolian and Ruthenian lands.
